An '''epiphytic fungus''' is a [[fungus]] that grows upon, or attached to, a living [[plant]]. The term [[epiphyte|epiphytic]] derives from the Greek ''epi-'' (meaning 'upon') and ''phyton'' (meaning 'plant').
==Examples== Many examples of epiphytic microorganisms exist.<ref name="review">[http://www.ejbiotechnology.info/content/vol3/issue1/full/4/index.html Endophytic Microorganisms:A Review On Insect Control And Recent Advances On Tropical Plants<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The [[ergoline]] alkaloids found in ''[[Convolvulaceae]]'' are produced by a [[seed]]-transmitted epiphytic [[claviceps|clavicipitaceous]] fungus .<ref name="ergoline">{{cite journal | last1 = Steiner | first1 = U | last2 = Ahimsa-Müller | first2 = MA | last3 = Markert | first3 = A | last4 = Kucht | first4 = S | last5 = Gross | first5 = J | last6 = Kauf | first6 = N | last7 = Kuzma | first7 = M | last8 = Zych | first8 = M | last9 = Lamshöft | first9 = M | last10 = Furmanowa | first10 = Miroslawa | last11 = Knoop | first11 = Volker | last12 = Drewke | first12 = Christel | last13 = Leistner | first13 = Eckhard | title = Molecular characterization of a seed transmitted clavicipitaceous fungus occurring on dicotyledoneous plants (Convolvulaceae) | journal = Planta | volume = 224 | issue = 3 | pages = 533–44 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16525783 | doi = 10.1007/s00425-006-0241-0 | display-authors = 8 }}</ref>
