A '''sporodochium''' (pl. '''sporodochia'''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=bFjVCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA470&lpg=PA470&dq=sporodochium+explained&source=bl&ots=_FQDTm83aE&sig=PW77gWCkam0ASDXDD0uI5VKlR9c&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj6s6PK2OfVAhVKZVAKHdZUAe8Q6AEIOzAD#v=onepage&q=sporodochium%20explained&f=false|title=The Dictionary of Science for Gardeners: 6000 Scientific Terms Explored and Explained|last=Allaby|first=Michael|date=2015-09-05|publisher=Timber Press|isbn=9781604697155|language=en}}</ref>)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=FE6xqRZ-q-EC&pg=PA77&dq=sporodochium&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjf49fo2OfVAhXJ7hoKHcmeD3EQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=sporodochium&f=false|title=Principles of Plant Pathology|last=Dasgupta|first=M. K.|date=1988|publisher=Allied Publishers|isbn=9788170231929|language=en}}</ref> is a small, compact [[stroma (mycology)|stroma]] (mass of [[hypha]]e) usually formed on host plants [[parasitism|parasitised]] by mitosporic [[fungus|fungi]] of the form [[Order (biology)|order]] [[Tuberculariales]] ([[Deuteromycota|subdivision]] [[Deuteromycota]], class [[Hyphomycetes]]). This stroma bears the [[conidiophore]]s on which the [[asexual reproduction|asexual]] [[spore]]s or [[conidium|conidia]] are formed.

